That was kind of the challenge was to create this entire world. About that time I brought Brian Frout into it. We worked, we operated for the first year on just the vaguest of outlines knowing basically what the story was going to be about. But I wanted to design the characters first. Then after we had the characters together, the storyline grew. And actually, I was looking for a time to actually put this story down, to write it down. I needed a couple of days cleared. There are some things that are about 10 feet tall. So we're into all kinds of different creatures. And they were all designed by Brian Fraud, who's the English fantasy illustrator. and Brian has done just a wonderful job of designing both the creatures, their costumes, the entire world, the landscape, the castles, all of that was designed by Brian. But it has a very different look and it doesn't look anything like anything we've ever done before. I take it Brian sort of storyboarded the idea down in. He was doing design work, but actually we had other people doing storyboards for the whole film. Okay. Possibly how they're manufactured or how they're put together? well what the normal process and the reason that it sort of took a number of years to accomplish this film was that Brian would do an original sketch and then we would turn that we would go to have one of our sculptors then sculpt the figure and then we would mock it up so that we could manipulate it and then we would try moving this thing, and these things moved in different ways. We would videotape a test, and then we'd all sit around and look at the test and decide what should be done about it. And then Brian would normally redesign the character. So that's one of the reasons it was a long development. Yeah, right. The whole problem was whether or not we could design a world that the audience would believe. that you would believe that this was a world with all the depth in our own world there are so many things that you look around and you accept a very complicated world but all these things have a sort of a depth to them, there's a lot of stuff behind everything and so in that sense Brian went about designing these creatures the whole culture the symbolism behind the different kinds of creatures and their lifestyles. They only added a new layer on top, and it was all kind of really awful, and we figured it probably smelled terrible. But it was all brocades and rich, very rich fabrics. So, you know, it's that kind of thing. You go through the thinking process of what this evolution was. And you do that not only for the creatures but for their environment and the places where they live. We had these trees that would walk around, and we had areas of the mud that was alive. But from our standpoint it was very valuable to have gone through this process to know what's there. We know what's on the other side of that tree that you're not seeing. Yeah, I would tend to think that would make it the realism of the scene come more alive for you and you'd be able to pass that on when you found it. Yeah, I think so. otherwise you end up with just a surface. I think we have something here that has more depth to it because of the time that we put into that. You and Frank Oz co-directed the pictures, is that right? Yes, that's right. How does something like that work? How does one co-direct a picture? Well, we were both performing in this film, which is one of the reasons that co-directing made sense, because when you're inside a set and you're actually performing, it's rather difficult to be the person outside that's running the film unit and also seeing the scene with a sense of perspective. So we found it very useful. Generally, if I was performing, Frank was kind of running things and vice versa. And we worked very closely together throughout the whole pre-production and post-production. And Frank and I have worked together for many years, So it's not an uncomfortable thing at all. We think very much alike. And our image of this film, I think, was something that we, you know, shared the feelings of. So it was quite an easy process. Okay. Um, I read up and researched, and I believe I saw a special on PBS not long ago on, I bet you hosted on puppetry. and it went into how y'all produce the show and everything. But could you give a little bit of a sort of visual explanation of what it's like on a set? Well, let's see. Because we were operating most of these characters from below, the sets were all built about four feet off the floor. And we would be operating with a, oh, sometimes through holes in the floor or sometimes a character would be there and there would be several people around operating cables going to one particular character. If you saw the credits on ET, you saw how many people were credited with operating ET. And we had dozens of characters that were all about that complicated. So you can imagine we would have lots and lots of performers. and we were always using a video system, a through-the-lent television camera, so we would be operating with television monitors. If I was inside a character operating him, I would be wearing a television monitor on my chest and all the other people who were helping to operate that same character would also be watching television monitors. So it was that kind of a process. Sort of high-tech artistry. Yes, yes. We're using a lot of different kinds of technical and special effect mechanisms, radio control, marionette rigs, all of these things. But basically, they're all ways of assisting the performer create a performance. So despite the fact that it's high-tech, I really think of it as assisting a performance to happen because that is what everything revolves around, the quality of the performance itself. Yes, that's very good. Very good explanation. Let's see. This was filmed over in England, right? Yes, we were shooting at the L3 Studios, the same ones that have done Star Wars and Raiders of the Lost Heart. We did The Great Muppet Caper there also. Why was it shot over in England? Any particular reason? Mostly because we were there doing The Muppet Show, also in Elstry. And this film studio is about two blocks from where we were working. And I wanted to go straight from the end of The Muppet Show into The Great Muppet Caper. So while we were still doing that television show, we were doing the pre-production for the movie. If I had decided to do that in the United States, we probably would've had to do it about eight months later. You're talking a little while ago about some of the scenes and where you had to work from a hole underneath the set and stuff like that. Did you have a... I enjoyed reading a description of how you manipulated Kermit when you were doing the Muppet movie and the first scene in the swamp. Did you have any scenes that were as difficult is that Manning was at the USS Henson submarine that you were in? Well, let's see. I don't think – we never had anything that was quite that claustrophobic. I mean, fortunately, I'm not a claustrophobic person, so I don't mind being sprinched into a small space. But in the Muppet movie, in the great Muppet caper, we would very often find ourselves in a situation where we were out in the real world like riding in a taxi cab where there might be three or four of us jammed underneath where the seat would have been in a regular automobile. But since this film was all in a fantasy world which was designed for us to operate in, we virtually never had that same kind of discomfort. So all of our sets were designed with knowing that we wanted to be able to get underneath the ground or through a rock wall. So all of it was designed with trap doors or areas that could be removed. Yeah, okay. The basic premise behind the story is, I guess, the eternal conflict between good and evil. Well, it's that sort of thing. The basic story really relates to a young man growing up, facing the world, facing the evil powers and the unknown, and conquering fear. So in that sense, it's a very standard thing, standard fairytale myth basic story. Well, the story itself is complete in itself and so it doesn't lend itself to Dark Crystal 2 I don't think there will be a sequel as such We could set another story in this same world but I think we're kind of waiting until after this film opens to see how we feel about that Yeah Yeah, they had several fantasy movies out this summer, but none of them really seemed to capture the genre. In fact, I guess one of the last and best was The Wizard of Oz, and I was quite a part of it. So in that sense, I really hope you're successful at that because I really enjoyed the fantasy stories. Yes, to us it was a wonderful challenge. It was something we had a great time doing. and whether or not we are or we will be successful at it is something I have no idea yet. We won't really know until the film opens. Yeah, sort of a calculated gamble in that sense. Yeah. Okay. You still okay on time? Well, I'm late, but okay. I wanted to get just a little bit of background information on how you got started and the various programs that you worked on and stuff like that. And we can make this kind of brief if you'd like. Sure. Okay. The first question, of course, is how did you get started in all this? Well, I started just out of high school on local television in Washington, D.C. I started doing a little puppet show there that was on late at night. It was an 11.25 in the evening five-minute show. And I had that show while I was going to college and for the next few years. And during that time, the style of the Muppets sort of came together. Then I moved up to New York and started doing guest shots on variety shows and did the Jimmy Dean show, which was a country western show with our dog, Rolf. We did that for three years. did the Ed Sullivan show for a while, and about that time, Sesame Street came along. Sesame Street, we're in the process of working on our 14th season right now, so that's something that is still a part of our operation here. And The Muppet Show came along about, like, seven years ago, I guess. we did The Muppet Show we did 5 years of that which was 120 shows and they're dispersed in all of this our various and sundry television specials and a lot of guest shots that sort of brings us up to date I guess I suppose I guess it's kind of funny but wasn't River Duckies what really put you on the map? Which one? Remember the song Rubber Ducky? Rubber Ducky? Isn't that sort of what really put you on the map and grabbed a lot of public attention? I never would have thought of that. It may have. Rubber Ducky came out in the first season of Sesame Street and I think it made it to close to the top ten. Not quite all. I don't think it got up to about number 10. I don't think it got any higher than that nationally. But I think probably Sesame Street itself was something that the general audience became aware of us. Although before that, I think we were mostly known in the industry, I guess. Yeah, I can remember watching Sesame Street when it came out and really enjoying your work because the humor that you put into it seemed to be written on two levels. Adults would laugh at one thing, kids would laugh at another. Yeah. It was a fairly conscious decision in that we've always known that the television set is controlled by not only the little kids but also their parents and their older brothers and sisters. That sort of thing. yeah could you give a brief reason as to how you design the Muppets rather than working with traditional puppets or marionettes well let's see I don't know when I started let's see I started with no connection with any normal puppeteers or anything so I guess you know, not having a background in it, nor knowing hardly anything about it, I started in probably a fresh direction, coming mostly from just a different place, I suppose. Do you suppose it might have been that you're working in the medium of television that caused you to use the design where you could have more, I guess, facial expression on your characters rather than the static expression on marionettes and whatnot? Yeah, oh, certainly. Certainly. The fact that all of our original characters were designed just for television. We were probably one of the first people to do that because even Bert Kilstrom, whose work I had seen, and probably he was likely the major influence on me, I suppose, but even his work had started before television. and so it wasn't particularly designed for the medium. He was a kid at the time and so he was with me in a lot of the early days of our development and then slowly started doing voices. and a lot of his voice things really came into really great shape about the time we started on Sesame Street. Yeah, I think Frank's name is just highly appropriate for what he does. Yes. Speaking of voices, I know this, but this is just for the audience. Who does which voice is the really popular characters? Well, let's see. Frank does Fozzie Bear. Fozzie was sort of named for Frank Oz, too. I don't know if people realize that. But Frank does Fozzie and Piggy, Animal, Sam Eagle, on the Muppet Show, on Sesame Street he does Cookie Monster, Grover, Brute, and in Dark Crystal he's doing a character named Ogra. And he does The Chamberlain So Those are two of the major characters In The Dark Crystal Let's see What else? I do a character named Jen In The Dark Crystal And I was also performing On The Skeksis, The Ritual Master So more or less incidental character And on The Muppet Show I do Kermit Roth Waldorf, the chef, a few others, like Dr. T. The well and the hearty of the Muppet world. Yes, we've been doing that for a long time. And it's still a long time. We still have a good time doing that stuff. I can remember. I don't even remember where I saw this. But I thought it was on the Muppet Show because of Sesame Street. It was a segment where the Swedish chef was making a sandwich. And the subtitles were all in Chinese. Hmm. Well, that was the first time we used the Swedish Chef. And that was something, I'm quite sure this was, when on a pilot special we did for ABC. Many years ago, it was called A Muppet Show. Okay, that must be, I remember laughing so hard that I cried when I saw that. That was so hilarious. Gee, that's nice. That's nice. I've got to look at that show. I haven't seen that show myself in a long time. Okay, well, I think I've about covered... Oh, I have a guess here. If I was going to make a guess, I would guess that you're a computer games fan. Would I be guessing right? It's interesting. Not particularly. I grew up playing a lot of games, and I enjoy computer games, but I sort of never get around to doing it. I guess I have a busy life, and I don't... You know, we had an Atari... We have an Atari unit at home for the kids, which I've enjoyed playing some of those games. But I haven't really gotten into it. Okay. Missed my mark, what can I say? If a person was interested in doing what you do or going to work for somebody like you, what type of area would they study in, work in, do? What type of person are you looking for? Let's see. Well, I don't know. So it's different kinds of things. As a performer, for performers, I look for people who work with a sense of humor and a kind of ability of performing and focusing their performance in their hands. There are specific things one looks for in terms of puppeteering. But the whole film business right now is a very exciting time. And everybody is on the lookout for people with a lot of talent. Okay, well I'll take up plenty of your time there. I certainly do appreciate you taking time out to talk with me. Okay, good Dave. It was a pleasure. Okay, whenever we get the tapes cut together, I'll send you a copy of the completed shows. Great. That would be very nice. Okay. Thank you. Thank you much, Mr. Transit. Bye-bye. Bye-bye.
